---
title: Pan Fried Cod with Roasted Tomatoes and Lemony Risotto
description: Fish and risotto are two things that a lot of people, including some HelloFresh cooks, seem to be a bit wary about cooking. So, Mimi made this for them to show how simple (and delicious) it is to cook both of them. You can do it!
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/pan-fried-cod-with-roasted-tomatoes-24-d7f0cf13.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipecards/card/pan-fried-cod-with-roasted-tomatoes-24-295b29f2.pdf
author: HelloFresh
source: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipes/pan-fried-cod-with-roasted-tomatoes-24-5745ba64fd2cb999308b4567
servings: 2
course: main course
cuisine: Fusion
nutrition:
  calories: 500 kcal
  fat: 5 g
  saturated fat: 2 g
  carbohydrates: 82 g
  protein: 33 g
time required: 35 minutes
---

Pre-heat your #oven{} to 200 degrees. Cut the @onion{1}(cut in half through the root, peeled and chopped into roughly 1cm pieces).

Chop each @vine tomatoes{2} into eight wedges.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{} if you have one).

Pull the @marjoram{1/2}(leaves only, stalks removed and roughly chopped) leaves off their stalks and roughly chop the leaves.

Zest and juice the @lemon{1/2}(zested and juiced) and grate the @parmesan cheese{2}.

Put the tomatoes on a #baking tray{}. Mix together half the garlic and a quarter of marjoram with @olive oil{1%tbsp}, @salt{1/4%tsp} and a good grind of @pepper{a good grind}. Drizzle this over the tomatoes and leave them to the side.

Bring @water{1%l} to the boil in a #pot{} with the @vegetable stock pot{1}.

Meanwhile, pop the onion in a #saucepan{} with @butter{1%tbsp}(optional, or oil instead). Put on medium heat and cook for ~{5%minutes} until the onion is soft, then add the remaining garlic and three-quarters of the remaining marjoram. Stir together and cook for ~{30%seconds}.

Once the pan is smelling fragrant and garlicky, add the @risotto rice{1} along with @salt{1/4%tsp} and a good grind of @pepper{a good grind}, stir and cook for ~{1-2%minutes} until the rice looks lightly translucent around the edges. Meanwhile, put the tomatoes in your oven to cook for ~{20%minutes}.

Once you've cooked your rice for a minute, add in a ladle of your stock, stir, and when the stock has been absorbed by the rice, add another ladle of stock. Keep the pan on medium heat and continue adding stock (and stirring now and again while it cooks), letting it absorb before adding another ladle. The cooking time should take ~{20-25%minutes} and your risotto is done when your rice is "al dente".

> 'Al dente' simply means the rice is cooked through but has a tiny bit of firmness left in the middle.

When your risotto is cooked (you still want it slightly liquidy, not like porridge which has been cooked for too long!), add in the parmesan and some of the lemon juice. Stir, taste, and add more lemon juice, salt and pepper to taste. Put a #lid{} on and leave to the side off the heat.

Put a pan on medium heat with @oil{1%tbsp}. Season each fillet of @cod fillets{2} with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a good grind of @pepper{a good grind} on each side. Sprinkle the lemon zest over each fillet as well. Put the fillets in your pan skin-side down and cook for ~{3%minutes} before turning over to cook on the other side for ~{3%minutes}.

> Don't move your fish around when it's cooking skin-side down or it won't get a crispy skin!

Stir your roasted tomatoes into your risotto and serve in #bowls{} with your cod on top. Sprinkle over your remaining marjoram and enjoy!